# Standing approvals: the WHAT gate.
#
# Read by arbiter/src/standing_approvals.py. The privacy gateway
# checks every state-changing op (send_bitcoin, send_lightning)
# against the rules below AFTER the recipient address registry
# (§4.7) resolves the destination. First matching rule wins; no
# match = the gateway HITL-parks the call and refuses uniformly.
#
# The arbiter ships this file empty (literally `approvals: []`).
# Every state-changing call HITLs until you write a rule. That is
# the design - the friction is the pedagogy. Build working knowledge
# of what the AI is actually trying to do by reviewing each call in
# person at the directly-attached console; ratify the patterns you
# trust by adding them here.
#
# Schema:
#   - op:                 send_bitcoin | send_lightning
#     destination:        a registry token (5 Crockford-base32 + 1
#                         Damm32 check char, e.g. ABCDE4); or the
#                         literal 'any' for broader rules
#     max_amount_sats:    optional inclusive upper bound (sats);
#                         absence = any amount; for Lightning,
#                         amount_msats is rounded up to sats before
#                         this bound is checked
#     rationale:          optional free-text note for your own
#                         future self - what you approved, when,
#                         and why
#
# Discipline:
#   - Keep the file short. Long config = small surface of real human
#     oversight. Every line here is a future call that will NOT get
#     reviewed.
#   - Concrete over broad. Prefer narrow rules ("this token, up to
#     this much, for this reason") over `destination: any` blanket
#     allows; reserve `any` for cases where you've already accepted
#     that any registered destination is fair game (e.g., tiny LN
#     test payments).
#   - First match wins. If you stack rules, put the narrower ones
#     above the broader ones.
#
# Edit at the directly-attached arbiter console (the same KVM used
# to add entries to the recipient address registry). Changes are
# captured by the arb-auditability snapshot tree under
# arbiter/config/ - so the operator's edit history IS the audit
# trail.
#
# Per design-docs/origin/05--2026-05-05-0948-architecture-overview.md
# §4.1, §6, §7 and GLOSSARY 'Standing approvals'.

approvals: []

# === Examples (uncomment and edit) ==================================
#
# Pre-approve small Lightning sends to one specific recipient:
#
# approvals:
#   - op: send_lightning
#     destination: ABCDE4
#     max_amount_sats: 5000
#     rationale: Coffee shop, approved 2026-05-15 after 3 HITL reviews
#
# Mix a narrow Bitcoin rule with a broad LN test-payment allowance.
# The narrow rule is listed first because first-match wins:
#
# approvals:
#   - op: send_bitcoin
#     destination: FGHJK7
#     max_amount_sats: 100000
#     rationale: Monthly rent UTXO, approved 2026-05-20
#
#   - op: send_lightning
#     destination: any
#     max_amount_sats: 1000
#     rationale: Sub-1k-sat test payments to any registered dest
